Epoch:1 | IDEA | Scientist0:Thought: Keypoint detection in texture-less or symmetric objects remains a persistent challenge due to the lack of discriminative visual cues and inherent ambiguities in assigning semantic correspondences. While contrastive learning has shown promise in learning rich feature representations, it often fails under such ambiguous conditions because it assumes that augmented views are semantically distinct enough to form meaningful positive/negative pairs—this breaks down when symmetry or uniform textures create indistinguishable local patterns. Drawing inspiration from Paper 1’s focus on foreground localization via data-driven augmentation, Paper 2’s exploration of non-contrastive self-supervision for structured representation learning, and Paper 3’s integration of equivariance and disentangled perturbation modeling in 3D, I propose a novel framework that unifies uncertainty-aware embeddings with equivariant contrastive learning. The key insight is that instead of treating all keypoints equally, we should model *probabilistic* keypoint locations where uncertainty naturally arises (e.g., at symmetric extremities), while enforcing geometric equivariance so that learned features transform predictably under known symmetries (rotations, reflections). Furthermore, by incorporating hybrid supervision—leveraging sparse ground-truth annotations alongside self-supervised view consistency—we can guide the model to maintain semantic coherence even in low-signal regions. Unlike prior work that either ignores uncertainty (most contrastive methods) or treats symmetry as noise (standard data augmentation), our approach explicitly models both as first-class components of the representation learning process. This leads to more robust, interpretable, and generalizable keypoint detectors, especially in robotic manipulation or AR/VR settings where precise correspondence under ambiguity is critical.

