  "Idea": "We propose a novel non-contrastive framework, Uncertainty-Guided Equivariant Reconstruction Learning (UGERL), for robust keypoint detection in texture-less and symmetric objects by replacing traditional contrastive objectives with a disentangled, equivariance-enforced reconstruction paradigm grounded in probabilistic feature spaces. Unlike conventional contrastive methods that assume unambiguous correspondence between augmented views—failing when multiple configurations are geometrically valid due to symmetry or lack of texture—UGERL eliminates reliance on negative sampling and instead learns dense correspondences through structured transformation prediction and uncertainty-aware latent reconstruction. The core innovation lies in a dual-path variational autoencoder architecture: one branch encodes an invariant shape prior (shared across symmetric transformations), while the other captures transformation-specific residuals (e.g., rotation angle, reflection). These residuals are discretized using vector quantization into symmetry action tokens (e.g., 'rotate_90°', 'flip_z'), enabling explicit supervision of equivariant behavior. During training, pairs of transformed point clouds or images are generated under known SE(3) perturbations and object symmetry groups. The model is trained to reconstruct the target view by combining the shared shape prior with the predicted transformation residual, enforced through an equivariant decoder that ensures features transform consistently with input geometry. Crucially, each keypoint embedding is modeled as a Gaussian distribution, with variance reflecting both aleatoric (data-driven) and epistemic (model-driven) uncertainty. High-variance embeddings naturally down-weight contributions in the reconstruction loss, preventing overfitting to ambiguous regions. A lightweight supervised head uses sparse manual annotations only at non-symmetric, semantically salient keypoints (e.g., a valve on a cylinder) to anchor global semantics without disrupting symmetry-equivariant learning. We further introduce a curriculum where early stages use textured variants to bootstrap feature learning, gradually transitioning to bare geometry. This design enables the model to learn meaningful correspondences even when visual cues are absent, by leveraging geometric consistency and quantified uncertainty. Evaluation will focus on benchmarks like YCB-Inverse, LINEMOD-O, and synthetic texture-free CAD datasets, measuring keypoint reprojection error, pose estimation accuracy, uncertainty calibration (via NLL and ECE), and zero-shot generalization to unseen symmetric instances. UGERL offers significant advantages for robotic perception, where reliable, interpretable uncertainty and geometric consistency are critical for safe decision-making.",
